			<h1>Slugging Percentage (SLG)</h1>

			<div class=3D"entrytext">
			=09
<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-what-is-slugging-percentage">What is=
 Slugging Percentage?</h2>



<p><strong>Slugging percentage</strong>&nbsp;(aka&nbsp;<em>SLG</em>,&nbsp;a=
nd also called&nbsp;<em>Slugging Average</em>) is the number of&nbsp;total =
bases&nbsp;a player hits each&nbsp;at bat. It only includes hits (not walks=
 and hit-by-pitches) and assigns extra value to extra-base hits. This makes=
 it a good measure of a player=E2=80=99s power.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-how-is-slg-used">How is SLG used?</h=
2>



<p>Unlike batting average, SLG differentiates between kinds of hits. It val=
ues doubles more than singles; triples more than doubles; and home runs mor=
e than triples. Since extra-base hits are generally better than singles, it=
=E2=80=99s useful to have a stat that reflects that.</p>



<p>Since the league average in SLG is usually around .400, a good slugging =
percentage is above .400. The best hitters will have at least a .500 SLG.</=
p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-slugging-percentage-formula">Sluggin=
g Percentage Formula</h2>



<p>The slugging percentage formula is:</p>



<p><strong>SLG =3D (Singles&nbsp;+ (2 =C3=97&nbsp;Doubles)&nbsp;+ (3 =C3=97=
&nbsp;Triples)&nbsp;+ (4 =C3=97&nbsp;Home Runs)) =C3=B7&nbsp;<a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/At_Bats">At Bats</a></strong></p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list"></ol>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-slg-examples">SLG Examples</h2>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-using-slugging-percentage-formula-1"=
>Using Slugging Percentage Formula #1</h3>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s look a a real-life example to learn how to use the first s=
lugging percentage formula. During the 2024 season, <a href=3D"https://www.=
baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=3Djudgeaa01&amp;t=3Db&amp;year=3D=
2024">Aaron Judge</a> recorded 180 hits, 36 doubles, 1 triple, and 58 home =
runs in 559 at bats. First, we need to find how many singles Judge hit.</p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Subtract doubles, triples, and home runs from total hits. 180-(36+1+58)=
 =3D 85.</li>
</ol>



<p>Judge hit 85 singles. Now, let=E2=80=99s plug that into the slugging per=
centage formula.</p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Multiply Judge=E2=80=99s extra-base hits by their respective values. 2*=
36 =3D 72. 3*1 =3D 3. 4*58 =3D 232.</li>



<li>Add up the total bases from Judge=E2=80=99s hits. 85+72+3+232 =3D 392.<=
/li>



<li>Divide Judge=E2=80=99s total bases by his at bats. 392/559 =3D .701.</l=
i>
</ol>



<p>Judge had a .701 SLG in 2024.</p>



